IDC â€” Industrial Development Corporation

Development Finance Institution of South Africa

The Industrial Development Corporation ("IDC") of South Africa Limited was established in 1940 through an Act of Parliament and is fully owned by the South African Government. The IDC's priorities are aligned with the National Development Plan ("NDP"), Industrial Policy Action Plan ("IPAP"), and industry Master Plans.

  • Mandate: promote economic growth and industrial development
  • Co-Operation Agreement signed with PPR
  • Role: development finance and strategic support
  • Gazetted PPR as SIP 20e â€” Strategic Infrastructure Project

Note: The IDC has a contractual right to acquire an equity stake in the PPR project. IDC also contributed funds for the project development to PPR.

The Project

Catalytic green hydrogen & ammonia production in the Northern Cape

08

Overview of the Project

Project Background

PPR is a catalytic green energy project starting construction in 2028. Combining high yielding solar & wind, water from the Orange River, and air to produce green hydrogen and ammonia.

  • Phase 1 targets: 85,000+ tonnes of green ammonia per year
  • Utilizing 15,000+ tonnes of green hydrogen per year
  • First site assessments conducted in 2020
  • Wind mast installed July 2022 â€” confirms dominant night wind pattern
  • Location: Prieska, Northern Cape Province
  • Accessible via R357 and N10 national road

Power Reserve Concept

Integrated renewable energy to green ammonia production

Power Reserve Concept

Solar, wind and battery storage work in synergy to deliver stable, round-the-clock green energy for hydrogen electrolysis and ammonia synthesis.

Decarbonisation Impact

Drives decarbonisation of energy-intensive sectors, supports green chemical production, builds a resilient industrial ecosystem.

Location & Infrastructure

Strategic position in the Northern Cape with exceptional renewable resources

15

Location & Logistics

Prieska, Northern Cape, South Africa

  • Road: N10 national road (Upington to Port Elizabeth)
  • Rail: Prieska railway station â€” direct Transnet access
  • Rail North: Connection to Upington & Namibia
  • Rail South: Connection to De Aar & Port Elizabeth harbour
  • Water: Orange River â€” 3.5 km pipeline to site
  • Solar: Exceptional irradiance â€” Northern Cape advantage
  • Wind: Strong night wind from mountain range south of town
  • Grid: Eskom KRONOS MTS substation (400kV/132kV) within 30 km

05

Market Position

Competitive advantage in global green ammonia markets

17

Project Rationale & Competitive Advantage

Resource Advantage

Ample land, abundance of solar & wind resources with complementary day/night generation profiles. Northern Cape offers some of the highest solar yields globally combined with consistent night winds.

Exceptional Solar & Wind

Infrastructure Linkages

N10 national road, Transnet railway with direct station access, port connections to Port Elizabeth, and 355mm water pipeline from the Orange River.

Road, Rail & Water

Export Markets

European, American, and Japanese markets offer strong demand. SA green ammonia is cost-competitive in Europe with import incentives and evolving green molecule policies.

Global Demand

Policy Alignment

Aligned with South Africa's Hydrogen Strategy, gazetted as SIP 20e Strategic Infrastructure Project. Government support through IDC partnership and regulatory framework.

SIP 20e & IDC
18

Market Size

Both domestic and export markets can absorb PPR's production

South Africa

  • Demand projected at 1 Mt/year ammonia and 0.8 Mt/year green hydrogen by 2030
  • Green ammonia becomes cheaper than grey at gas prices above ~$105/MWh
  • Key clients: Sasol, Omnia, Foskor, AECI, leading mining firms

European Markets

  • Key markets: Germany, Netherlands, Belgium, Spain, France
  • Projected demand: ~7 Mt/year hydrogen, ~10 Mt/year ammonia by 2030
  • Target sectors: fertilisers, chemicals, industrial heating, mobility

🌏 Asia-Pacific â€” Emerging Export Corridor

Japan targets 3Mt/yr clean ammonia by 2030; South Korea aims for ~3Mt/yr clean hydrogen â€” over 80% imported. Singapore is positioning as a regional hydrogen trading hub. Together, these markets represent 5Mt+ annual import demand by 2030, making Southern Africaâ€“Asia one of the most significant emerging green ammonia trade corridors globally.
